        </div>
        <p>Much like the infastructure portions of almost every software design that"s ever been written. Look at your codebase. Is there something in there, some remnant of infrastructure that was built with the greatest of hopes and expectations, only to be roundly replaced when you understood the problem better?</p>
        <p>Removing that code might be too hard now, because nobody writes perfect software. Some brittle tests somewhere might flare up, or a method call somewhere might explode. </p>
        <p>And yet that code sits there, inside your digital walls.</p>
        <p>Software Design is like building houses. The construction continues long after the thing is "finished", and you end up living with the choices you make for a long time, usually forever. </p>
        <p>And sometimes, in the night, you hear odd noises carried by those old ducts.</p>

